1 (b) During the third trimester of pregnancy between the 27th and
2 36th week of gestation or as soon thereafter as practicable; and
3 (c) At delivery for a pregnant woman who:
4 (1) Should be routinely tested for infection with syphilis, as
5 recommended by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention of
6 the United States Department of Health and Human Services;
7 (2) Lives in an area designated by the Division as having
8 high syphilis morbidity;
9 (3) Did not receive prenatal care; or
10 (4) Delivers a stillborn infant after 20 weeks of gestation.
11 3. A qualified serological or rapid test for syphilis is one
12 recognized as such by the State Board of Health.
13 4. If the test is made in a state laboratory, it must be made
14 without charge.
15 5. If a serological , rapid or physical examination test
16 performed pursuant to subsection 1 shows that a pregnant woman is
17 infected with syphilis, the physician, other person, non-hospital
18 medical facility, emergency department or labor and delivery unit
19 shall:
20 (a) If the physician, other person, non-hospital medical facility,
21 emergency department or labor and delivery unit is capable of
22 providing treatment for syphilis, seek the consent of the pregnant
23 woman to begin such treatment and, if such consent is obtained,
24 commence treatment; or
25 (b) If the physician, other person, non-hospital medical facility,
26 emergency department or labor and delivery unit is not capable of
27 providing treatment for syphilis, seek the consent of the pregnant
28 woman to refer her for such treatment and, if such consent is
29 obtained, issue the referral.
30 6. If the pregnant woman objects to the taking of the sample of
31 blood or the serological or rapid test, the sample must not be taken
32 and the test must not be performed.
